## Scope of this companion

This vignette accompanies the GRASS methods paper. It is a parallel
reference: the paper is self-contained for review, while this companion
carries the procedural detail and auxiliary diagnostics a practitioner
running `grassr` may want at hand. Section numbering does not parallel
the paper.

Content moved here from earlier paper appendices during the 2026-05-04
appendix consolidation. **The paper does not cite this vignette**; this
is a free-standing artifact for `grassr` users.

---

## 1. Notation glossary

Symbols used throughout the package and the paper:

- `Y` --- the $N \times k$ binary rating matrix; rows are subjects,
  columns are raters.
- `pi_hat` --- observed marginal positive rate.
- `tau2_hat` --- between-subject variance of the per-subject mean call
  rate (sample-side, computed from `Y`).
- `Se_j`, `Sp_j` --- per-rater sensitivity and specificity, inferred
  from the rating matrix, not against external truth.
- `q` --- diagonal-DGP rater quality; $\mathrm{Se}_j = \mathrm{Sp}_j = q$
  for every rater under the diagonal case the surfaces are calibrated on.
- `q_hat` --- implied panel quality recovered from an observed
  coefficient. Surfaced on the Report Card as the endpoints of the 95%
  consistency band (the quality levels consistent with the observed
  value); also the inversion each coefficient contributes to `delta_hat`.
- `delta_hat` --- cross-coefficient implied-quality spread, in quality
  percentage points, over PABAK, mean AC1, and Fleiss kappa.

---

## 2. Recovering $\hat q$ from an observed coefficient

For each agreement coefficient, `position_on_surface()` inverts the
closed-form expectation curve to recover $\hat q$ at the observed
coefficient value.

- **PABAK**: algebraic inverse, $\hat q = \tfrac{1}{2}(1 + \sqrt{\mathrm{PABAK}})$.
- **Fleiss $\kappa$, Krippendorff $\alpha$, AC1, ICC**: 501-point
  $q$-grid lookup with linear interpolation between the two nearest
  grid points where the curve crosses the observed value.
- **Out-of-range observations**: clamped to the boundary $q$ value
  with a `clamped = TRUE` flag.

---

## 3. ICC and the subject-prevalence distribution

The Report Card prints ICC alongside PABAK, AC1, and Fleiss
$\kappa$, but with a `[distribution-sensitive]` marker,
and ICC is excluded from the cross-coefficient stability signal
$\hat\delta$ by construction.

The agreement-family coefficients each have a closed-form
expectation that depends only on the panel marginal $\hat\pi_+$ and
the rater quality $q$. ICC depends additionally on the full
distribution $F$ of subject-level positive probabilities $p_i$ across
the rated subjects --- the shape of how the underlying positive rate
varies from one subject to the next. Two studies can both have an
overall positive rate of 30% and yet differ on whether that 30% comes
from a clear class of obvious-positives (high between-subject variance)
or from a mass of borderline-50/50 cases (low between-subject
variance). The agreement-family coefficients can't tell those two
studies apart at the panel level. ICC can, and so its reference
surface must commit to a specific $F$.

The bundled `grassr` reference covers a 48-point logit-normal grid in
$(\mu, \tau^2)$ plus four discrete-mixture profiles (uniform,
bimodal-low-high, skew-rare-positive, and similar shapes). A panel
whose true $F$ sits cleanly inside that grid reads ICC's surface
percentile faithfully. A panel whose $F$ sits between grid points or
under a different family carries a distribution-mismatch cost that the
agreement-family percentiles do not. This is why ICC carries a `[distribution-sensitive]`
marker on the Report Card and does not enter $\hat\delta$.

**Variant selection** (ICC(1,1), ICC(2,1), ICC(3,1)) follows the
Koo and Li (2016) decision tree on both the inter-rater and
intra-rater axes. The package exposes each variant through the
`metric` argument of `position_on_surface()`. The four-question
decision tree (same-rater-set / rater sampling / type / definition)
is reproduced with worked examples per branch in the package help
files.

---

## 4. Coefficient recovery: the full diagnostic

The paper's App C carries the lead recovery table
plus the asymmetry-cost figures. This
companion expands the same dataset across the full grid.

---

## 5. $\hat\delta$: the matched-null percentile convention

**What $\hat\delta$ is.** Each agreement coefficient inverts to its own
implied panel quality $\hat q$ on the shared $(q, \pi_+)$ reference. If
the calibration model held exactly, PABAK, mean AC1, and Fleiss
$\kappa$ would imply the same quality; $\hat\delta$ is the max--min
spread of those implied qualities, in quality percentage points, and
measures cross-coefficient model discordance (Option B, ratified
2026-07-05). Typical aligned panels sit at roughly $0.01$--$0.5$ quality
pp. ICC never enters $\hat\delta$; Krippendorff $\alpha$ left the family
at 0.6.0 and does not re-enter.

**The flag.** The flag is not a threshold crossing. $\hat\delta$ is
reported as its **percentile on the null distribution of $\hat\delta$
at the matched $(k, N, \hat q)$ cell** — the distribution of
implied-quality spread among simulated panels where nothing is wrong,
at the user's design and estimated panel quality. Flags are conventions
on that percentile, read with the mid-p convention at ties: **caution
at the 95th, divergent at the 99th**. The card prints the matched cell,
its draw count, and any design snap. At $k = 2$ the spread is
`not_applicable`: the two-coefficient family (PABAK, AC1) implies
identical quality by construction, so no discordance can be observed,
and asymmetry assessment routes to the pairwise/bounds path.

**Why a percentile, not a fixed cut.** The null distribution of the
implied-quality spread moves with panel quality (tight sampling
distributions at high $q$ turn small coefficient disagreements into
larger implied-quality spreads), and at small $N$ it is a mixture whose
extreme quantiles are not stably invertible — including a point mass at
$\hat\delta = 0$. Reading the observed $\hat\delta$'s ECDF position on
the matched null — exactly how every coefficient on the card is already
read — is stable where quantile inversion is not, holds its
false-positive rate at every quality by construction, and degrades
honestly: at very low quality and small $N$ the null is so wide that no
observable disagreement exceeds chance, and the percentile says so.

**Calibration.** The null ECDFs are generated through the production
pipeline itself (`check_asymmetry()` per draw: real normalization,
constant-rater dropping, clamp-guard), pooled over prevalence. The grid
was regenerated 2026-07-06 under the Option-B implied-quality
definition: 440 $(k, N, q)$ ridges, roughly 22M panels in total with at
least 46{,}002 draws per ridge. The bundled ECDF ships the 385 ridges
with $k \geq 3$ (the flag is `not_applicable` at $k = 2$), each stored
on a fine 1% probability grid plus the 99.5th. Cells whose extreme tail
is not stably invertible carry a transparency flag in the bundled
object; the percentile reading is otherwise unaffected, its Monte Carlo
error staying well under half a percentile point at the given per-ridge
draw counts.

## 5b. Pairwise PABAK and pooled-reference recovery

When the divergent flag fires, the Report Card abandons the
panel-aggregate summary and routes to a pairwise PABAK matrix plus
per-rater pooled-reference $(\widetilde\Se_j, \widetilde\Sp_j)$.

**Why PABAK at the pair level.** PABAK is the framework's pairwise
coefficient because under symmetric raters its closed-form expectation
reduces to $E[\mathrm{PABAK}] = (2q-1)^2$, a function of rater quality $q$
alone --- independent of prevalence and of the subject-prevalence
distribution $F$. Pairwise
reading needs that property because every rater pair has its own
observed marginal $\hat\pi_{+, ij}$, and those per-pair marginals can
move substantially with rater asymmetry. Cohen's $\kappa$ at the pair
level is prevalence-attenuated (the $\kappa$ paradox of
Byrt, Bishop, and Carlin (1993), the original motivation for PABAK); AC1's chance
term carries a milder but non-zero prevalence dependence; ICC at
$k = 2$ is degenerate because one pair of raters per subject leaves
the variance decomposition under-identified.

**Pooled-reference identifiability.** The pooled-reference estimates
are label-flip clean conditional on the panel-majority direction
matching the truth direction: the reference is the observable panel
majority rather than a latent class, so the estimates do not depend on
which mode an EM solver lands in. They read each rater's profile
relative to whichever direction dominates the panel. Under a 2:3
panel where the minority direction happens to be the truth direction,
the pooled-reference inverts and reads each rater's profile backwards.

**Empirical recovery (54-cell Monte Carlo).** A sweep over
$k \in \{3, 5, 7\}$, $\pi \in \{0.10, 0.30, 0.50\}$, asymmetry
magnitude $A \in \{0.10, 0.20, 0.30\}$, and both shared-bias and
split-bias configurations at $N = 200$ with $500$ replications per
cell:

- Pooled-reference recovers each rater's true bias direction in $94\%$
  of split-bias in-majority-direction rater-replicates (rate improving
  in $k$ from $90\%$ at $k = 3$ to $97\%$ at $k = 7$).
- Correctly inverts the direction in $98\%$ of minority-direction
  rater-replicates --- exactly as the conditional predicts.
- Mean bias on $\widetilde\Se_j$ is $0.06$ and on $\widetilde\Sp_j$ is
  $0.03$ at $A \geq 0.20$.

The pooled-reference summary is meaningful only at $k \geq 3$ (no
rest-of-panel to pool against at $k = 2$) and is noisier on subjects
where the panel is split. The package reports the per-rater pool size
$\widetilde n_j$ alongside each pooled estimate so the reader can see
how much information backs each one.

---

## 6. Worked code examples per Report Card branch

A small helper generates an `N x k` rating matrix under the
paper's diagonal DGP at a stated `seed`, `k`, `N`, per-rater
`Se`/`Sp`, target prevalence `pi`, and logit-normal spread
parameter `F_sigma2`:

```{r dgp-helper, eval = TRUE}
library(grassr)

simulate_panel <- function(seed, k, N, Se, Sp, pi, F_sigma2 = 0.25) {
  stopifnot(length(Se) == k, length(Sp) == k)
  set.seed(seed)
  mu_logit <- qlogis(pi)
  p_i <- plogis(rnorm(N, mu_logit, sqrt(F_sigma2)))
  C   <- rbinom(N, 1L, p_i)
  Y   <- matrix(0L, N, k)
  for (j in seq_len(k)) {
    Y[, j] <- rbinom(N, 1L, ifelse(C == 1L, Se[j], 1 - Sp[j]))
  }
  Y
}
```

### Aligned case (paper §4.1)

```{r aligned-example, eval = TRUE}
# Se = Sp = 0.85, k = 5, N = 1000, seed = 5
Y_aligned <- simulate_panel(
  seed = 5L, k = 5L, N = 1000L,
  Se = rep(0.85, 5), Sp = rep(0.85, 5),
  pi = 0.08
)
card_aligned <- grass_report(Y_aligned)
card_aligned
```

The three agreement coefficients land within ~1 pp of each
other on their reference surfaces; the panel is *aligned* and
the primary coefficient (PABAK) is safe to cite. ICC is
reported alongside with `[distribution-sensitive]` since its
reference surface depends on the full subject-prevalence
distribution rather than on `(q, pi_hat)` alone.

### Divergent case (paper §4.2)

```{r divergent-example, eval = TRUE}
# op_strong panel: R1,R3,R5 at Se=0.95/Sp=0.75; R2,R4 inverted
# k = 5, N = 1000, seed = 6, balanced prevalence
Y_divergent <- simulate_panel(
  seed = 6L, k = 5L, N = 1000L,
  Se = c(0.95, 0.75, 0.95, 0.75, 0.95),
  Sp = c(0.75, 0.95, 0.75, 0.95, 0.75),
  pi = 0.50
)
card_divergent <- grass_report(Y_divergent)
card_divergent
```

All three agreement coefficients return values around 0.49
and land at nearly the same pooled percentile (~67-69), yet
their *implied qualities* disagree: $\hat\delta$ is 0.25
quality pp, the 99.5th percentile of the matched null. The
*divergent* flag fires; the panel-aggregate summary is
suppressed; the Report Card emits the pairwise PABAK matrix
and per-rater pooled-reference `(Se_tilde, Sp_tilde)` against
the panel-majority of the other `k - 1` raters.

### $k = 2$ counterexample (paper §4.3)

```{r k2-example, eval = TRUE}
# High-quality k = 2 panel: Se = Sp = 0.97, pi = 0.08, N = 200
Y_k2 <- simulate_panel(
  seed = 17L, k = 2L, N = 200L,
  Se = rep(0.97, 2), Sp = rep(0.97, 2),
  pi = 0.08
)
card_k2 <- grass_report(Y_k2)
card_k2
```

Single-pair high-quality panel: PABAK and AC1 land near the
top of the design's achievable range (95th-96th pooled
percentile), consistent with panel quality 0.95-0.99.
$\hat\delta$ is `not_applicable` at $k = 2$ --- the
two-coefficient family cannot disagree --- so asymmetry
assessment would route to the pairwise and Hui-Walter bounds
path.

